{
  "answer": "**Several works in the corpus reflect on labor or work proper to humans, often in the context of social duties, productive activity, or distinction from natural forces or non-human production. The most direct discussions appear in ancient Indic *smṛti* texts (law codes) prescribing occupations (*vrtti* or *dharma*) by social class (*varṇa*), and in 19th-century French liberal economic treatises distinguishing human labor (*travail*, *industrie*) as essential for creating value.**\n\n### Indic *Smṛti* Texts (Proper Occupations by *Varṇa*)\nThese texts systematically outline what work is fitting for humans based on birth, aptitude, and cosmic order, with prohibitions on crossing class lines except in necessity. Chapter 10 of *Manusmṛti* is the most explicit and extensive treatment.[^1][^2]\n\n- **Manusmṛti** (*Laws of Manu*, ch. 10): Declares the duties of the four *varṇas* (Brāhmaṇa, Kṣatriya, Vaiśya, Śūdra) and mixed castes. Brāhmaṇas teach/study Vedas (primary), then warrior duties if needed; Vaiśyas tend cattle/trade; Śūdras serve. \"Abiding in their own duties\" (*svadharma*) is key; deviation risks degradation.[^3] Work is proper when aligned with one's class to uphold *dharma*.[^4]\n\nSimilar rules appear in other *smṛti*s, though less comprehensively:\n\n- **Yājñavalkya Smṛti** (ch. 1): Discusses *varṇa* duties implicitly in inheritance, marriage, and law, prioritizing class-proper roles.[^5]\n\nOther *smṛti*s (*e.g.*, Kātyāyana, Nārada, Paraśara) touch on *varṇa*-specific penalties and roles but lack dedicated chapters like Manusmṛti's.[^6]\n\n### French Economic Treatises (Human Labor as Productive/Distinctive)\nThese Enlightenment/19th-c. works philosophize labor as inherently human—combining will, skill, and foresight—versus animal instinct or inert nature. Proper human work advances liberty, property, and society.\n\n- **Traité de la propriété (Charles Comte, both vols.)**: Goods \"exist only by means of human labor\"; slave societies \"debase human labor.\" Labor proper to humans creates utility/property from nature.[^7][^8]\n\n- **Nouveau traité d'économie VOL II (Charles Dunoyer, ch. 14)**: Critiques economists excluding human maintenance from \"productive capital.\" Humans are \"the most precious\" agents; proper labor reproduces forces for societal good, unlike \"null\" idlers.[^9] Nature aids but requires human direction.[^10]\n\nNo works frame it as uniquely distinguishing humans from animals (searches for such yielded zero results). Poetry (*e.g.*, Cynewulf, Iqbal) and other genres lack sustained reflection.\n\n[^1]: *Manusmṛti*, [ch.10 overview](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/10/translation/).\n[^2]: *Manusmṛti*, [work wiki](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/wiki/_work.card.md) (distinctive: \"his own *varna*\", \"his own dharma\").\n[^3]: *Manusmṛti* ch.10, [p-b34355](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/10/translation/#p-b34355).\n[^4]: *Manusmṛti* ch.10, [opening p-4999b4](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/10/translation/#p-4999b4).\n[^5]: *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, [work wiki](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/wiki/_work.card.md).\n[^6]: *E.g.*, *Kātyāyana Smṛti* ch.63 (nearest to Manusmṛti ch.10 per wiki).\n[^7]: *Traité de la propriété VOL I* ch.5, [p-4ec7ba](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/05-de-lappropriation-des-choses-en-general/translation/#p-4ec7ba).\n[^8]: *Traité de Législation VOL IV* ch.17, [p-807487](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-iv-bca040/17-de-l-influence-qu-exercent-les-peuples-possesseurs/translation/#p-807487).\n[^9]: *Nouveau traité d'économie VOL II* ch.14, [wiki key passage p-803317](/works/charles-dunoyer-nouveau-traite-deconomie-vol-ii-d6ae03/14-iv-des-conditions-auxquelles-toute-industrie-peut-/wiki/14-iv-des-conditions-auxquelles-toute-industrie-peut-.card.md).\n[^10]: *Nouveau traité d'économie VOL II* ch.14, [p-6a59b3](/works/charles-dunoyer-nouveau-traite-deconomie-vol-ii-d6ae03/14-iv-des-conditions-auxquelles-toute-industrie-peut-/translation/#p-6a59b3).",
